[30;1m1647 | [0m[35m- Instances of :class:`.RelStorage` no longer use threading locks by[0m
[30;1m1648 | [0m[35m  default and hence are not thread safe. A ZODB :class:`Connection[0m
[30;1m1649 | [0m[35m  <ZODB.interfaces.IConnection>` is documented as not being[0m
[30;1m1650 | [0m[35m  thread-safe and must be used only by a single thread at a time.[0m
[30;1m1651 | [0m[35m  Because RelStorage natively implements MVCC, each Connection has a[0m
[30;1m1652 | [0m[35m  unique storage object. It follows that the storage object is used[0m
[30;1m1653 | [0m[35m  only by a single thread. Using locks just adds unneeded overhead to[0m

[30;1m1413 | [0m[35m- Substantial performance improvements for PostgreSQL, both on reading[0m
[30;1m1414 | [0m[35m  and writing. Reading objects can be 20-40% faster. Writing objects[0m
[30;1m1415 | [0m[35m  can be 15-25% faster (the most benefit will be seen by history-free[0m
[30;1m1416 | [0m[35m  databases on PostgreSQL 9.5 and above). MySQL may have a (much)[0m
[30;1m1417 | [0m[35m  smaller improvement too, especially for small transactions. This was[0m
[30;1m1418 | [0m[35m  done through the use of prepared statements for the most important[0m
[30;1m1419 | [0m[35m  queries and the new `'ON CONFLICT UPDATE'[0m

[30;1m33 | [0m[35mRelStorage tests are timing tests with strict tolerances. For example,[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35mwe set a lock timeout of 0.1s, fail to get a conflicted lock, and[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35massert that the time taken to fail was no longer than 0.1s. With[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35mpgBouncer in the way, that test (sometimes) fails by taking anywhere[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35mfrom 0.11 to 0.14s.[0m

[30;1m100 | [0m[35m    at any level besides ``SERIALIZABLE``, and one locks the *odd*[0m

[30;1m102 | [0m[35m    rows ``FOR UPDATE`` *or* in shared mode, if they happened to use[0m

[30;1m72 | [0m[35mWe keep ``new_oids`` in a separate database file beside the primary[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mdatabase file. This is because *any* write to a database causes an[0m

[30;1m152 | [0m[35mdatabase size.[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35mRelStorage deliberately stores information in the database about the[0m
[30;1m155 | [0m[35mobject references it discovered during packing. The next time a pack[0m
[30;1m156 | [0m[35mis run, this information is used for objects that haven't changed,[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35mmaking it unnecessary for RelStorage to discover it again. In turn,[0m
[30;1m158 | [0m[35mthis makes subsequent packs substantially faster when there are many[0m

[30;1m524 | [0m[35m        # resolution. So we reverse the order and rely on NOWAIT to prevent[0m
[30;1m525 | [0m[35m        # deadlocks. (We try to mitigate time spent[0m
[30;1m526 | [0m[35m        # waiting to take exclusive locks by running a quick check for[0m
[30;1m527 | [0m[35m        # readCurrent errors first). If there are no readCurrent[0m
[30;1m528 | [0m[35m        # errors, we have a chance to fix any conflicts.[0m
